"smart_sources:000 Zettelkasten/One way to help increase tumour specificity is to incorporate additional receptors on the T-cell that operate as Boolean functions..md": {"path":"000 Zettelkasten/One way to help increase tumour specificity is to incorporate additional receptors on the T-cell that operate as Boolean functions..md","class_name":"SmartSource","history":[{"blocks":{"000 Zettelkasten/One way to help increase tumour specificity is to incorporate additional receptors on the T-cell that operate as Boolean functions..md#":true,"000 Zettelkasten/One way to help increase tumour specificity is to incorporate additional receptors on the T-cell that operate as Boolean functions..md#One way to help increase tumour specificity is to incorporate additional receptors on the T-cell that operate as Boolean functions. These include “OR” (which is activated by one antigen or the other on a tumour cell surface), “AND” (only activated when recognising both antigens on tumour cells), “NOT” (inactivated when encountering one antigen on normal cells), or “synNotch” (first primed and induced by one tumour-specific but heterogenous antigen then activated by a homogeneous antigen). An example of one such function is the \"split-receptor\" method. [[The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient.]]{1}":true,"000 Zettelkasten/One way to help increase tumour specificity is to incorporate additional receptors on the T-cell that operate as Boolean functions..md#References":true},"mtime":1709479558757,"size":936,"hash":"9e52117860473534a47ae12fc074b6ecdeea65d6e1f3813072935e9f830fa5a9"}],"embeddings":{"TaylorAI/bge-micro-v2":{"vec":[-0.00191503,0.00470982,-0.01850745,0.03986219,0.0292287,-0.00271921,0.01848028,-0.02979835,-0.00724711,-0.00089386,-0.00845964,-0.0115131,-0.03778923,-0.05453741,0.03446367,-0.00019092,0.04529278,-0.00788175,0.0043643